 stages depending on the needs of businesses in that particular sector.  In some cases support is provided at a very early stage of development t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o help bring new ideas into a sector.  For example a feasibility study competition was recently run to bring new ideas into the offshore wind supply chain.  In other cases, demonstration is needed very near </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commercialisation in order to prove readiness </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of a new technology.  The low carbon vehicles demonstrator is a good example of this.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Technology Strategy Board works to interact with other public funders to ensure the spread of support across different stages is right.  For example, in offshore win</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d,  DECC programmes existed to support later stage development and demonstration projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> so we decided to run earlier stage funding for supply chain technologies and worked with DECC to co-brand and communicate the two funding streams to make them easier</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to understand for business.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Technology Strategy Board works very closely with the Research Councils to pull through academic research into the industrial base.  Many programmes are co-funded with the Research Council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Energy Programme in order to fa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cilitate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">collaboration between businesses and academia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, the competition for novel solutions to offshore renewable energy infrastructure problems, opening in December 2013 is co-funded with £0.5m from the research councils to specifically pull</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through academic excellence in HVDC technologies in the UK into the commercial sector.   Overall, about 20% of Technology Strategy Board spend </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">grants go to research organisations partnering with businesses to develop new products and technologies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Support for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">energy technologies as they are deployed can become very expensive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, for example through the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Renewables</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Obligation or proposed Contracts for Difference for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">renewables</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.   Scale-up of manufacture, process automation and efficiencies of scale</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can provide significant cost savings, but need a significant scale to realise them.   There is always a balance to be made between spending public money </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">supporting deployment and scale-up</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and supporting earlier stage R&amp;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">D.   To be successful in the long term, both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">need to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be supported. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition to different stages of development, it is important to support different kinds of organisations in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">distinct </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ways.  Often very innovative solutions are developed by small or mi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cro companies who need different kinds of support when compared to a large multinational</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  The Technology Strategy Board continues to develop its SME support package, linking up with other BIS initiatives such as Growth Accelerator.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Catapult </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">centres also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> focus on SME support in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">defined </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sectors.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Technology Strategy Board and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ouncils are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">planning a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">new</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> joint</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">funded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> approach in energy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the form o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘energy catalyst’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  This is designed to provide a continuous ‘escalator‘ of funding t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hat can take an idea from concept all the way to commercialisation.  It is intended to build on experience in the biomedical and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">agritech</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industries where such an instrument is used very successfully.  The intention is to better support the best new techno</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">logies through an ‘always open’ fund that is committed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">across </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the medium to long term. This will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provide better certainty of funding over the long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> term that companies can access at the right time for them, and that can support ideas all the way </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to the po</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">int where they are investor-ready.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What is the impact of the short-term funding timelines on private sector investment?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our interactions with businesses in the low carbon sector tell us two things relevant to this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">question:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:11.54pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">market </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">policy uncertainty is likely to have a greater </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">effect than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> innovation funding uncertainty.  Without a relatively secure view of the future market for new products, it is very difficult to persuade businesses, especially SMEs to invest in R&amp;D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; and,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:11.54pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">changing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> funding levels, priorities and start/stop funding is difficult for businesses because they often feel they have to apply for support when it suits the public sector to provide it rather than when they need it.  They may also find they get support initiall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y but then have no way of taking that to the next stage if the funding stops without any follow-up.</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Technology Strategy Board publishes strategies and delivery plans to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">instil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> confidence in their activities years in advance.  Our developing plans with the Research Councils referred to in Paragraph 22 above are focused on helping to address </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">issues. The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> LCICG’s strategy document</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, to be published shortly will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> help to clarify</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> priorities for future support across LCICG</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (See LCICG response for further detail).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How should DECC ensure that its remaining capital allocation for low carbon innovation will be spent wisely, after two years of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">under spend</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> No comment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s beyond those </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in LCCIG response.</span></l